{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SgSYQujw4BZTQUaBAttjSp","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have a thorough picture. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` mixed-case branch — `0/4/5` substitutions\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2 (`title-extractor.ts`, `title-extractor.test.ts`)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe change is logically sound and the sequencing rationale (1→letter before 0/4/5 so that newly-formed lowercase neighbors enable subsequent replacements) is correct. The main concern is that the ALL_CAPS branch inside `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (lines 870–874) is now incomplete relative to both its mixed-case sibling and the standalone `applyBlindOcrRepair` — a real consistency gap. There is also a subtle but real false-positive risk with `4→a` and `5→s` that is worth explicitly noting.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority — ALL_CAPS branch of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` is incomplete\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:870`\n\n**Impact**: A title like `C4FÉ CRÈME` or `5PICE BLEND` that is classified as ALL_CAPS at the token level passes through the ALL_CAPS branch and the `4` and `5` are not repaired, even though `applyBlindOcrRepair` (the full-string path) would fix them. The divergence is silent: no error, just a corrupted character surviving into the output.\n\n**Root Cause**: The ALL_CAPS branch was written when only `0` had been added to the repair set. Each new digit was added to the standalone `applyBlindOcrRepair` function first (which operates on whole strings), but the per-token ALL_CAPS branch inside `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` has never been brought to parity.\n\nThe current state of the three code paths:\n\n| Substitution | `applyBlindOcrRepair` ALL_CAPS | `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` ALL_CAPS | `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` mixed-case |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `1→I/i/l` | yes (unconditional) | yes (unconditional) | yes (guarded) |\n| `0→O/o` | yes (guarded) | yes (guarded) | yes (guarded) — new |\n| `4→A/a` | yes (guarded) | **missing** | yes (guarded) — new |\n| `5→S/s` | yes (guarded) | **missing** | yes (guarded) — new |\n| `¡→I` | yes | missing | yes |\n| `€→E` | yes | missing | yes |\n| `ÍÌ→I` | yes | missing | n/a |\n\nThe gap for `4` and `5` in the ALL_CAPS token branch is now especially visible because the mixed-case branch they sit beside handles them.\n\n**Solution**: Add `4` and `5` (and arguably `¡`/`€`) to the ALL_CAPS token branch, keeping the same uppercase-adjacent guard pattern already used for `0`:\n\n```typescript\nif (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n  return token\n    .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n    .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\")\n    .replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n    .replace(/5(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"S\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])5/g, \"S\");\n}\n```\n\nWhether to also add `¡→I`, `€→E`, and `ÍÌ→I` depends on whether those glyphs can appear in all-caps tokens; the standalone function includes them, so if the token path is supposed to be a faithful per-token version of the same logic, they belong here too.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority — False-positive risk for `4→a` is higher than for `0→o`\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:883`\n\n**Impact**: The digit `0` looks nearly identical to `O`; its false-positive risk in real text is very low. The digit `4` does not look like `a` in most OCR fonts — it is an uncommon OCR confusion. A title containing a real numeral adjacent to lowercase letters (e.g. `\"Phase 4a trial\"`, `\"4-season blend\"`, or ingredient-adjacent text like `\"yields 4 servings\"`) would be incorrectly mutated.\n\nThe guarding (`[a-zà-ż]` adjacency) provides good protection for standalone numbers (`\"4 eggs\"` has no lowercase letter immediately adjacent), but compound forms like `\"step4a\"` or `\"room4two\"` — while unusual in recipe titles — would fire.\n\n**Root Cause**: The guard was designed with `0→o` confidence in mind (very safe) and applied uniformly to `4→a` and `5→s` without calibrating for their lower OCR confusion frequency.\n\n**Suggestion**: This is a deliberate design choice that may be entirely appropriate given the observed corpus of OCR errors. The right mitigation is not to remove the rules, but to ensure there are test cases that exercise the guard correctly — both firing cases (`\"S4uce\"` → `\"Sauce\"`) and non-firing cases (`\"Step 4 of the recipe\"` must not change). If those cases are already covered in the eval loop (the `iter.txt` trajectory suggests an active empirical loop), the risk is managed. If not, add explicit unit tests.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority — Duplicate JSDoc block\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:889`\n\nThere are two consecutive JSDoc comments before `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase` (lines 889–893 and 894–897). The first is stale from a prior refactoring and describes the function inaccurately. This causes documentation tools and IDE hovers to show the wrong description.\n\n```typescript\n// Lines 889–893: this block is orphaned/stale and should be removed\n/**\n * Apply blind OCR digit-for-letter repair without dictionary lookup.\n * Used to generate additional candidates for early-position lines where\n * positional evidence is strong enough to justify speculative repair.\n */\n/**  ← this is the real doc, line 894\n * Apply blind OCR repair to mixed-case text...\n```\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions\n\n**Suggestion 1 — Ordering of `¡`/`€` vs guarded digit rules**\n\n`¡→i` and `€→e` are unconditional (no adjacency guard), which is a reasonable choice — those Unicode codepoints have essentially no legitimate use in recipe text. However, they currently run before `0/4/5` substitutions (lines 879–880 before 881–886). Since those symbols cannot be adjacent to a digit in any meaningful OCR confusion, the ordering has no effect on correctness. Worth a brief comment noting the intentional unconditional treatment, to prevent a future reader from assuming it's an oversight:\n\n```typescript\n// ¡ and € are unambiguous OCR artifacts in recipe text — no adjacency guard needed\n.replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n.replace(/€/g, \"e\")\n```\n\n**Suggestion 2 — Consider a table-driven approach as the rule set grows**\n\nThe function now has 10 chained `.replace()` calls in the mixed-case branch, and the ALL_CAPS branch (once completed) will have 7. Each new digit-for-letter confusion added in a future iteration requires editing both branches in parallel and keeping them consistent — which is precisely the gap that produced the HIGH priority issue above.\n\nA shared substitution table would make the symmetry structural rather than disciplinary:\n\n```typescript\nconst DIGIT_LETTER_SUBS: Array<[RegExp, RegExp, string]> = [\n  // [lookbehind pattern, lookahead pattern, replacement]\n  // populated from a data structure, or just: [digit, lowerReplacement, upperReplacement]\n];\n```\n\nThis is a refactoring suggestion for a later iteration, not a blocker.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The sequencing rationale (1-repair before 0-repair to unlock lowercase neighbors) is correct and the comment context in `normalizeOcrTitle` is clear about the pipeline ordering.\n- Using per-token `isAllCaps` detection inside `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` rather than a whole-string check correctly handles mixed-case text that contains isolated ALL_CAPS words (e.g., a title like `\"PIEROGI with sauce\"`).\n- The adjacency guard pattern (`(?<=[a-zà-ż])` and `(?=[a-zà-ż])`) is appropriately conservative — it substantially reduces false positives compared to unconditional replacement.\n- The extended `À-ÿ` / `à-ż` ranges in the character classes correctly cover Polish and other Latin-extended characters throughout."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a7c398c2aa3000b04 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 28666\ntool_uses: 12\nduration_ms: 94347</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2b7f6f9f-d196-4c23-a5a2-5f5e40472414","uuid":"97577a74-de10-48a3-9f87-2a59d4d0754d","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the following change to `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`. The change extends the mixed-case branch of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` to add `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s` substitutions with lowercase-adjacent guards.\n\n**The change (around line 876):**\n\nBefore:\n```typescript\nreturn token\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, oneLetter)\n  .replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, oneLetter)\n  .replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n  .replace(/€/g, \"e\");\n```\n\nAfter:\n```typescript\nreturn token\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, oneLetter)\n  .replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, oneLetter)\n  .replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n  .replace(/€/g, \"e\")\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0/g, \"o\")\n  .replace(/0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n  .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\")\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])5/g, \"s\")\n  .replace(/5(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"s\");\n```\n\n**Context:**\n- There's also an ALL_CAPS branch (lines 870-875) and a separate `applyBlindOcrRepair` function (line 899) that handles all-caps text with the same `0/4/5` substitutions.\n- The `¡/€` rules have no adjacent-letter guards (unconditional), while `0/4/5` use guards.\n- The `1→oneLetter` runs before `0→o` intentionally — so `S01e` with `l` goes: `S0le` → `Sole` (0 now has `l` lowercase to its right).\n- All 37 tests pass.\n\nPlease review for:\n1. **Implementation completeness** — are all cases handled correctly, any edge cases missed?\n2. **Code quality** — is this the right level of complexity?\n3. **Codebase consistency** — should similar changes be applied elsewhere (e.g., the ALL_CAPS branch in `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` already has `0` but not `4/5`; the standalone `applyBlindOcrRepair` function has all of them)?\n\nFile path: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`","agentId":"a7c398c2aa3000b04","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have a thorough picture. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` mixed-case branch — `0/4/5` substitutions\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2 (`title-extractor.ts`, `title-extractor.test.ts`)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe change is logically sound and the sequencing rationale (1→letter before 0/4/5 so that newly-formed lowercase neighbors enable subsequent replacements) is correct. The main concern is that the ALL_CAPS branch inside `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (lines 870–874) is now incomplete relative to both its mixed-case sibling and the standalone `applyBlindOcrRepair` — a real consistency gap. There is also a subtle but real false-positive risk with `4→a` and `5→s` that is worth explicitly noting.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority — ALL_CAPS branch of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` is incomplete\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:870`\n\n**Impact**: A title like `C4FÉ CRÈME` or `5PICE BLEND` that is classified as ALL_CAPS at the token level passes through the ALL_CAPS branch and the `4` and `5` are not repaired, even though `applyBlindOcrRepair` (the full-string path) would fix them. The divergence is silent: no error, just a corrupted character surviving into the output.\n\n**Root Cause**: The ALL_CAPS branch was written when only `0` had been added to the repair set. Each new digit was added to the standalone `applyBlindOcrRepair` function first (which operates on whole strings), but the per-token ALL_CAPS branch inside `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` has never been brought to parity.\n\nThe current state of the three code paths:\n\n| Substitution | `applyBlindOcrRepair` ALL_CAPS | `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` ALL_CAPS | `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` mixed-case |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `1→I/i/l` | yes (unconditional) | yes (unconditional) | yes (guarded) |\n| `0→O/o` | yes (guarded) | yes (guarded) | yes (guarded) — new |\n| `4→A/a` | yes (guarded) | **missing** | yes (guarded) — new |\n| `5→S/s` | yes (guarded) | **missing** | yes (guarded) — new |\n| `¡→I` | yes | missing | yes |\n| `€→E` | yes | missing | yes |\n| `ÍÌ→I` | yes | missing | n/a |\n\nThe gap for `4` and `5` in the ALL_CAPS token branch is now especially visible because the mixed-case branch they sit beside handles them.\n\n**Solution**: Add `4` and `5` (and arguably `¡`/`€`) to the ALL_CAPS token branch, keeping the same uppercase-adjacent guard pattern already used for `0`:\n\n```typescript\nif (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n  return token\n    .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n    .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\")\n    .replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n    .replace(/5(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"S\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])5/g, \"S\");\n}\n```\n\nWhether to also add `¡→I`, `€→E`, and `ÍÌ→I` depends on whether those glyphs can appear in all-caps tokens; the standalone function includes them, so if the token path is supposed to be a faithful per-token version of the same logic, they belong here too.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority — False-positive risk for `4→a` is higher than for `0→o`\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:883`\n\n**Impact**: The digit `0` looks nearly identical to `O`; its false-positive risk in real text is very low. The digit `4` does not look like `a` in most OCR fonts — it is an uncommon OCR confusion. A title containing a real numeral adjacent to lowercase letters (e.g. `\"Phase 4a trial\"`, `\"4-season blend\"`, or ingredient-adjacent text like `\"yields 4 servings\"`) would be incorrectly mutated.\n\nThe guarding (`[a-zà-ż]` adjacency) provides good protection for standalone numbers (`\"4 eggs\"` has no lowercase letter immediately adjacent), but compound forms like `\"step4a\"` or `\"room4two\"` — while unusual in recipe titles — would fire.\n\n**Root Cause**: The guard was designed with `0→o` confidence in mind (very safe) and applied uniformly to `4→a` and `5→s` without calibrating for their lower OCR confusion frequency.\n\n**Suggestion**: This is a deliberate design choice that may be entirely appropriate given the observed corpus of OCR errors. The right mitigation is not to remove the rules, but to ensure there are test cases that exercise the guard correctly — both firing cases (`\"S4uce\"` → `\"Sauce\"`) and non-firing cases (`\"Step 4 of the recipe\"` must not change). If those cases are already covered in the eval loop (the `iter.txt` trajectory suggests an active empirical loop), the risk is managed. If not, add explicit unit tests.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority — Duplicate JSDoc block\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:889`\n\nThere are two consecutive JSDoc comments before `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase` (lines 889–893 and 894–897). The first is stale from a prior refactoring and describes the function inaccurately. This causes documentation tools and IDE hovers to show the wrong description.\n\n```typescript\n// Lines 889–893: this block is orphaned/stale and should be removed\n/**\n * Apply blind OCR digit-for-letter repair without dictionary lookup.\n * Used to generate additional candidates for early-position lines where\n * positional evidence is strong enough to justify speculative repair.\n */\n/**  ← this is the real doc, line 894\n * Apply blind OCR repair to mixed-case text...\n```\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions\n\n**Suggestion 1 — Ordering of `¡`/`€` vs guarded digit rules**\n\n`¡→i` and `€→e` are unconditional (no adjacency guard), which is a reasonable choice — those Unicode codepoints have essentially no legitimate use in recipe text. However, they currently run before `0/4/5` substitutions (lines 879–880 before 881–886). Since those symbols cannot be adjacent to a digit in any meaningful OCR confusion, the ordering has no effect on correctness. Worth a brief comment noting the intentional unconditional treatment, to prevent a future reader from assuming it's an oversight:\n\n```typescript\n// ¡ and € are unambiguous OCR artifacts in recipe text — no adjacency guard needed\n.replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n.replace(/€/g, \"e\")\n```\n\n**Suggestion 2 — Consider a table-driven approach as the rule set grows**\n\nThe function now has 10 chained `.replace()` calls in the mixed-case branch, and the ALL_CAPS branch (once completed) will have 7. Each new digit-for-letter confusion added in a future iteration requires editing both branches in parallel and keeping them consistent — which is precisely the gap that produced the HIGH priority issue above.\n\nA shared substitution table would make the symmetry structural rather than disciplinary:\n\n```typescript\nconst DIGIT_LETTER_SUBS: Array<[RegExp, RegExp, string]> = [\n  // [lookbehind pattern, lookahead pattern, replacement]\n  // populated from a data structure, or just: [digit, lowerReplacement, upperReplacement]\n];\n```\n\nThis is a refactoring suggestion for a later iteration, not a blocker.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The sequencing rationale (1-repair before 0-repair to unlock lowercase neighbors) is correct and the comment context in `normalizeOcrTitle` is clear about the pipeline ordering.\n- Using per-token `isAllCaps` detection inside `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` rather than a whole-string check correctly handles mixed-case text that contains isolated ALL_CAPS words (e.g., a title like `\"PIEROGI with sauce\"`).\n- The adjacency guard pattern (`(?<=[a-zà-ż])` and `(?=[a-zà-ż])`) is appropriately conservative — it substantially reduces false positives compared to unconditional replacement.\n- The extended `À-ÿ` / `à-ż` ranges in the character classes correctly cover Polish and other Latin-extended characters throughout."}],"totalDurationMs":94347,"totalTokens":28666,"totalToolUseCount":12,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1326,"cache_read_input_tokens":25059,"output_tokens":2280,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1326},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
